<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-07-30T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-07-30T03:00:00-05:00" n="506" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d506">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/6213: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-07-30T16:00:00+08:00">July 30, 1936—4
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received July 30—1:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>419. Reuter under London date line July 29th states rumors persist China
                            seeks 20,000,000 pounds loan for economic development from Great
                            Britain, France, Belgium and Japan. Also reports Japanese press
                            extending feelers for revival Anglo-Japanese friendship. Repeated to
                            Peiping, by mail to Nanking.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>